Reason: To predict the melting point of 3-nitrobenzyl bromide, we will start with the basic unit, benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. Compared to benzene, 3-nitrobenzyl bromide has two additional functional groups: a nitro group (-NO2) and a benzyl bromide group (-CH2Br). The nitro group is an electron-withdrawing group that decreases electron density in the benzene ring and creates stronger intermolecular forces like dipole-dipole interactions, which can significantly increase the melting point; we can estimate this effect to be around +80 degrees Celsius. The benzyl bromide group introduces a larger and heavier atom (bromine) into the structure, which increases the molecular weight and Van der Waals forces, also leading to a higher melting point, estimated at +40 degrees Celsius. However, benzyl bromide is also an alkyl halide which can make the molecule more polar and while it does increase the molecular weight, it might not have as strong of an effect due to its influence on molecular packing, this effect is estimated to be a smaller increase. When combined, we predict an overall increase in the melting point due to these substituents.
